The following variable will not work:
{code}
 1.0-${bamboo.varName}
{code}
if one isn't using the bamboo.varName in his version; instead, he is calculating the Build number as part of the Build script that bamboo executes. So the tasks that Bamboo runs as part of the Build, determine the version number.

According to the [RESP API documentation|https://docs.atlassian.com/bamboo/REST/4.0/#idp137056], the url:
 http://myhost.com:8085/bamboo/rest/api/latest/result/{projectKey}should return all the build results starting from the latest build. Now if the latest build state is known due to problems like the build hung, the REST call skip it. In general all builds with unknown state are skipped. 

You can however retrieve this build via API if the build number is known using something like http://myhost.com:8085/bamboo/rest/api/latest/result/{projectKey}-{buildkey}

In later version of Bamboo 5, users are only able to add the child plans and the parent  plans are calculated automatically and added. In older versions, we can configure the child and parents in same UI. Since we have changed this, the description note should be changed. It is currently stated as 
{quote}
You can configure this plan to trigger child plans or be triggered by parent plans on this page
{quote}

In Bamboo, when I create a MSBuild Task,

in "Options" input box, I wanted to add a msbuild property "ReferencePath" and it contained 2 paths:

{quote}C:\Program Files (x86)\WiX Toolset v3.7\SDK{quote}
{quote}C:\Program Files (x86)\DGIT\bin{quote}

So in the options, the input was"
 {quote}/p:ReferencePath="C:\Program Files (x86)\WiX Toolset v3.7\SDK;C:\Program Files (x86)\DGIT\bin"{quote}

This would cause a build error because of "MSBUILD : error MSB1006: Property is not valid.". I guess the reason for this is:

When Bamboo handles this input box, it would delete all the quotation marks from the input.

The workaround would be (Cheating):

In the "Project File", the Bamboo takes whatever is in the box, wrap it in a pair of quotation marks. So we can inject code into it by adding another pair of quotation marks:

{quote}DGiT.Build.Wix.CA.sln" /p:ReferencePath="C:\Program Files (x86)\WiX Toolset v3.7\SDK;C:\Program Files (x86)\DGIT\bin{quote}

When a remote agent cannot publish its artifacts, the job is still marked as successful.
The job reports no error, for example:
{noformat}
Unable to publish artifact [Linux core system]:
{noformat}
This might happen when the remote agent tries to connect to Bamboo through a reverse-proxy that can't transfer the file (e.g. wrong max body size).

